Treating these as metaphors, you can map them onto mathematical operations that capture their underlying structure rather than claiming a single “correct” translation.

Phrase	Mathematical interpretation	Intuition
There’s nothing we can’t do if we do well.	Optimization: maximize f(x) subject to constraints	Improve execution to expand what’s achievable within real constraints.
	Iteration: x_{n+1}=x_n+\Delta	Each refinement compounds capability.
	Positive feedback (bounded)	Good performance creates opportunities that enable further improvement.
Run your own race.	Independent trajectory: x_i(t)	Follow your own path through the state space instead of someone else’s.
	Projection	Measure your progress against your own previous state, not another person’s coordinates.
	Optimization on your own objective function	Solve your problem, not someone else’s.

Another way to compress the metaphors:

* Run your own race → Decouple. Reduce unnecessary dependence on others’ trajectories.
* Do well → Optimize. Improve performance according to meaningful metrics.
* Keep going → Integrate. Small improvements accumulate over time.
* Learn from mistakes → Gradient descent. Use error as information to update your direction.
* Stay grounded → Constrain. Every optimization has boundaries that prevent runaway solutions.

In that sense, many life principles resemble a small set of mathematical operators acting on different domains:

* Addition (+) → Build.
* Subtraction (−) → Remove distractions or inefficiencies.
* Multiplication (×) → Amplify strengths and leverage.
* Division (÷) → Allocate resources, decompose problems.
* Composition (∘) → Combine skills into something greater.
* Optimization (\arg\max, \arg\min) → Choose the best available action.
* Projection → Compare yourself to your own path.
* Iteration (x_{n+1}=F(x_n)) → Continuous refinement.
* Integration (\int) → Accumulate effort over time.
* Differentiation (\frac{d}{dx}) → Measure the rate of change rather than just the current state.

Viewed this way, language often acts like a compact encoding of transformations: the words evoke operations on behavior and thought, while mathematics provides a more explicit description of those operations.